R two-day course for Annalect

Niels Richard Hansen, Nina Munkholt Jakobsen

June 22 and 28, 2017

Preparation

Before the course, you need to do the following:

  • Visit the course webpage: math.ku.dk/~richard/Annalect/, where you find links to all course resources.
  • Make sure that you can bring a laptop for the course, and that you have permissions to install software on it.
  • Install R and RStudio on your laptop.
  • Test that you can start RStudio and that it appears to open without errors.

In addition, it’s a really good idea to:

  • Watch RStudio Essentials Part 1.
  • Install the tidyverse R package.
  • Install the shiny R package.

Resources

Course slides, examples and exercise templates and solutions will constitute the main teaching material. It will become available online.

We will introduce some main ideas from the textbook R for Data Science by Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemund. The book will not be covered as is, but references will be provided whenever appropriate.

Primary resources

  • Slides, examples, exercises and solutions (available online from June 22).
  • Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemund, R for Data Science, abbreviated RfDS.
  • R Markdown articles: rmarkdown.rstudio.com/articles.html
  • knitr webpage: yihui.name/knitr/
  • Shiny resources: shiny.rstudio.com
  • Help pages, e.g. ?ggplot, ?mutate or ?lm.

Secondary resources

Recommended books and online resources covering aspects of R dealt with in the course but in greater depth:

  • Winston Chang, Cookbook for R (Graphs).
  • Hadley Wickham, ggplot2: Elegant Graphics for Data Analysis. Textbook covering how ggplot2 implements Grammar of Graphics, the theoretical underpinning of the ggplot2 R package.
  • Hadley Wickham, Advanced R. Textbook on R programming.
  • Hadley Wickham, R packages. Textbook on R package development.
  • The R Project for Statistical Computing: www.r-project.org
  • R Development Core Team, The R Manuals. These manuals constitute the official documentation of the R language as developed and supported by the R Core Team.
  • RStudio online learning: www.rstudio.com/online-learning/
  • Jenny Bryan, Happy Git and GitHub for the useR. Git and GitHub usage for version control.
